It all starts with the plate-job. A kid's gnocchi career, I mean. In my family, when you were little you would be appointed to gently pick up gnocchi from the kneading table where grandma was cutting them out, and take them to another room where a tablecloth was laid out to receive them for the resting time. Only later on were you allowed to make your own gnocchi. ...I'm sure other Italian children were luckier: I've always suspected that my grandma was just a bit jealous of her gnocchi-master role! 
Anyhow, you don't need to start from the lowest ranks of the gnocchi-making ladder - lucky you! Join my gnocchi workshop tomorrow and jump straight to nonna-level gnocchi skills! üë©üèº‚Äçüç≥üë®üèΩ‚Äçüç≥üë©üèª‚Äçüç≥üë©üèø‚Äçüç≥

Gnocchi times are happy times! This is the food that I most associate with the warm feeling of togetherness and joie-de-vivre that is  so typical of the Italian food culture. Gnocchi remind me of Sundays spent with grandma and grandpa, carving those little potato pillows one by one, waiting for lunchtime. Since a few years, they also remind me of the many new friends I made over my periodical gnocchi workshops in Amsterdam.

Neaples loves cultural remix.  If you visit the city, you can't miss the architectural clues of this habit. If you try Neapolitan cuisine, you'll find all kinds of influences, from Greek-Roman, to Arabic, to French and Spanish. Some of these are quite easy to spot by paying attention to food  names. Take "graffe", for example: delicious ribbons of sugar-sprinkled deep-fried dough. The word should sound familiar to German speakers... Any guesses?

Reflecting on friendship & the kitchen.

In the past few years, the deepest friendships I started, the most meaningful, personal and fun exchanges, had something to do with food. As someone who is well aware of her cultural/gastronomic heritage, but eager to learn from and engage with others with a different culture mix, the kitchen has become a playground, and some of my playmates real friends who share the same taste for life and discovery. 
When I started AsSoupAsPossible.com  I honestly couldn't ask more of it than the solitary joys of researching and writing. What I did not expect was that this little gastronomic storytelling project of mine would put me in touch with a number of smart, passionate and friendly people from all paths of life.
They are the people I have interviewed for the blog and YouTube channel or met at my food events, but also the pizza obsessives, the sourdough amateurs, and simply those who read my stories and reached out to share their thoughts or just say hi.

Some of them became unforgettable friends, whom I associate with specific foods, recipes and flavours... Confirming my belief that food is never "just food" and there are always multiple layers of stories, memories and feelings to it.

Last week my friend T. moved back to the US and gifted me with pretty much everything from her diverse pantry. We met almost two years ago, after starting a conversation through As Soup As Possible's Facebook page.
Last night I felt the urge to use some of the ingredients I have inherited from her. I decided to improvise with the Japanese ones.

That's how I made yet another memory with T., even if she was already miles away.

Of course the caption of this photo could have just read "my first maki"... but that wouldn't have cut it.

For a change, "pizza in teglia" instead of Neapolitan style.
It was a quick way to recycle some leftover dough from yet another type of pizza pie (with endive filling) that I had baked on Sunday. No reason to toss good dough: I stored it in the fridge, took it out early this morning, and used it as a base for this quick but scrumptious lunch break. It was easier than getting something from a store, and I know exactly what's in it. 
The topping: grated sheep ricotta and parmigiano between two layers of grated potatoes, rosemary, extra virgin olive oil, salt and black pepper. 
Do I need to mention this was a sourdough crust? 
Yet another way to be grateful for my sourdough starter Elvira!

I can proudly announce that my first sauerkraut experiment was a success: it didn't kill me and it came out quite appetising, two outcomes I never took for granted. 
It took me months to gather the courage to open the first jar, but surviving the test made me cocky.
Now I feel like pickling the life out of every pickleable vegetable I can put my hands on! Hide your spare glass jars, lock up your organically grown veggies! I'm coming for them! üòà

Struffoli is the name of one of the most ancient recipes in the rich repertoire of Neapolitan cuisine.
The word indicates the tiny balls of deep-fried dough coated in honey and decorated with candied fruit and spiced hard candies that you will find on every pastry shop window in Naples in the weeks around Christmas and New Years Eve.

This year I'm making a weekly batch to give my followers the chance to try this festive treat.

I just shared the recipe to assoupaspossible.com/struffoli.
Try to make them at home or - if you live in Amsterdam- reserve one of the boxes I'm making every weekend in December (link in bio). #struffoli #neapolitancuisine #Christmas #gift #blog #foodblogger #recipe #baking #christmasrecipes #blogpost #food #italianfood #napoli #expatlife #italianfoodbloggers
